			>
			"I like this approach, in general"<br><br>Me too, and it's a copycat of WoW. WoW and Blizzard in general is very strong on customization, where you start with a basic theme and playstyle and you can tweak it a variety of ways. WoW is a testament to that, and in particular, the druid class presents the very same arrangement as it would have in EQ... well except for the fact it might be even more diversified in WoW.<br><br>By the way, what passes as "AAs" in WoW can be reconfigured at will, which is definitely a good point of the game, and another way of keeping the flexibility even with 2 lines of AAs. <br><br>"1. Is the magnitude of the change sufficient to reach that goal? (Corollary: is the magnitude of the compensating decrease too high?)<br><br>2. Do we have the tools (spells, skills) sufficient to reach that goal?"<br><br>My answer to no1 is... if it is not sufficient to reach the goal... its pretty close. It would be in the area of practical number crunching to determine more precisely.<br><br>My answer to no2 is... we dont have the sufficient tools on the healing side, but we have plenty of them on the DPS side.<br><br><br>Bluetiger	
