		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			Well I'm actually playing a level 70 cleric right now, and besides that have mainly spent my time as Beastlord and a bit as a Shaman.  But the changes that are proposed sway me towards wanting to try out a druid instead.  It's not that I fear being replaced; it's that I like being able to get the goodies for myself (the new ones, plus the traditional stuff like foraging, porting, tracking, invising) and not getting the short end of the stick.  From what I can see (and feel free to respond with your own opinions), the appeal of playing a druid is it's fun with all your special abilities and versatility, being useful alone or as part of a group, with the only real drawback being that you may not be the first choice for healer or dps/evacer.<br><br>This whole stance proposal sounds sort of like an EQ2-ish class diversification, where you choose one type of proficiency over another, except here you get to have the best of both worlds.  Now from an outsider's point of view, I would say if the druid community is split between those who want to dps better and those who want to heal better, let them be able to make a specialization/class-diversification choice one way or the other and be done with it (but not necessarily penalizing the status quo healing or dps when one path is chosen over the other).<br><br>If every class could successfully solo with the efficiency of a druid, the game really wouldn't be the same (it would lose some of the appeal to me), but anyhow, I can't see how that could feasibly happen across the board, despite the warrior example of further increased defenses with less aggro control.<br><br>I wouldn't call this class balancing though, because this is basically giving more versatility to perhaps the most versatile of existing classes.	
		</td></tr>
